{
  "text": "Taken together, our findings showed for the first time that human IL-27 acts as a potent antitumor agent for MM that may block MM progression and metastatic bone resorption. Additional antitumor effects may be operated in vivo by IL-27 through enhancement of CTL, natural killer, and CD8 + T-cell cytotoxicity (1). On this ground, IL-27 seems to represent a novel, promising therapeutic agent for MM patients, whose prognosis remains grim, based on its multifunctional activity. An additional argument in favor of this proposal is the low toxicity shown by IL-27 in animal models, likely in relation to the low induction of IFN-γ in vivo [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "18062143"
